Country's important families, including that of Sir Francis Drake. His half-brother was the explorer Sir Humphrey Gilbert. In 1578 Raleigh was granted a patent to explore and colonize “unknown lands” in America. In the 1580s he was granted extensive estates in Munster (Ireland), in reward for his suppression of the Desmond Rebellions."],"variants":[{"name":"Raley","meanings":["English: variant of   Raleigh  ."]},{"name":"Rawleigh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Orlo.","English: variant of   Raleigh  , reflecting a common pronunciation."]},{"name":"Riley","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name chiefly from High Ryley in Accrington (Lancashire) and Riley in Kirkburton, which was in the manor of Wakefield (Yorkshire). In some cases the name may derive from Riley Farm in Eyam (Derbyshire), Royley in Royton (Lancashire), or Rylah in Scarcliffe (Derbyshire). The placenames all come from Old English <i>rȳge</i> ‘rye’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: from <b>Ó Raghailligh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Raghailleach</i>’, Old Irish <i>Roghallach</i>. This is the name of a chieftain family in Cavan, related to the O'Rourkes. In Anglicized form it has also been confused with <b>Ó Raithile</b> found in Munster, usually Anglicized as <b>O'Rahilly</b> or   Rahilly  . See   O'Reilly  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Raleigh was born in 1300, in Farleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Raleigh, was 25 and his mother, Joan Tracy, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Beatrice Chaundos. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1300–":"1300–Surnud","1251–Male":"1251–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1339–1375":"1339–1375","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","1305":"1305","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1375":"1375","1275":"1275","1251":"1251","1339":"1339","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1300–":"1300–Kuollut","1251–Male":"1251–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1305–Female":"1305–Kuollut","1339–1375":"1339–1375","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1279–Female":"1279–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1375":"1375","1275":"1275","1251":"1251","1339":"1339","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1300–":"1300–Décédé","1251–Male":"1251–Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1305–Female":"1305–Décédée","1339–1375":"1339–1375","1275–Male":"1275–Décédé","1279–Female":"1279–Décédée","1305":"1305","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1375":"1375","1275":"1275","1251":"1251","1339":"1339","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Raleigh est né en 1300, à Farleigh, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, John Raleigh, avait 25 ans et sa mère, Joan Tracy, avait 22 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Beatrice Chaundos. Il est décédé à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1300–":"1300–Verstorben","1251–Male":"1251–Verstorben","1300–Male":"1300–Verstorben","1305–Female":"1305–Verstorben","1339–1375":"1339–1375","1275–Male":"1275–Verstorben","1279–Female":"1279–Verstorben","1305":"1305","1279":"1279","13